[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       else "crisis_routed" if ...
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    439[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       else "escalated"     if ...
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    440[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       else "abandoned"     if ...
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    441[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       else "other"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    443[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    444[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    445[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **What's wrong:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    446[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    447[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The two layers use different string values. The chat-reply layer reports the per-turn disposition in real time (useful for the channel UI to render different colors or icons). The audit-archive layer reports the conversation-level disposition based on close_reason and persistent counters. There is no mapping between them, so:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    448[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    449[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - A turn that returns `disposition="no_information_offered"` is invisible at the conversation level (gets folded into `contained` if it was the last turn before `user_session_end`).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    450[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - A turn that returns `disposition="clarification_requested"` similarly disappears.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    451[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - A turn that returns `disposition="handoff_offered"` is supposed to map to `final_disposition="escalated"` if the user accepts, but the counter that drives that branch is never updated (W2).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    452[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    453[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A learner reading the per-turn disposition strings expects them to flow into the conversation's audit record. They don't. The audit record's `final_disposition` is computed from a different, smaller set.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    454[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    455[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **How to fix:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    456[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    457[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Either (a) align the two vocabularies: rename the chat-reply dispositions to subset the audit dispositions plus a few per-turn-only states (`pending`, `clarifying`); or (b) document the layering explicitly in the demo:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    458[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    459[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    460[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Chat-reply dispositions describe the per-turn outcome (what the
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    461[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # UI should render). Conversation-level dispositions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    462[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # (final_disposition in the audit record) describe the entire
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    463[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # session and are computed from persistent counters and
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    464[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # close_reason. The two vocabularies overlap on "contained" and
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    465[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # "crisis_routed" but otherwise serve different purposes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    466[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    467[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    468[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Option (a) is more pedagogically clean; option (b) is the smallest change.
